How to use this guide
Don’t try to read this front to back in one sitting — it’s meant to be a reference you dip into. A few tips:
•Every data structure and algorithm has real, compilable C code.Copy it into a file, compile it,
run it, break it, fix it. That’s how this stuff actually sticks.
•Compile any example with:gcc filename.c -o output && ./output
•Ifyou’reshortontime, jump toPart 11first — it has a prioritized reading order for limited prep time.
•Terms are explained the first time they show up. If you hit something unfamiliar later, use Ctrl+F.
•Every major section ends with a short“Interview Radar”— the specific questions this topic tends
to show up as.
One honest note: this guide assumes you already know basic C syntax (variables, loops, if/else, functions). It
starts “from scratch” on theDSA-specificparts of C — pointers, structs, dynamic memory — because that’s
where most people’s foundations are actually shaky, and everything after depends on being solid there.
1

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
Part 0: C Essentials for DSA
Almost every DSA bug you’ll hit in C traces back to a shaky grip on one of these four things. Get comfortable
here and the rest of this guide gets a lot easier.
0.1 Pointers (the single most important concept in this guide)
A variable is a labeled box that holds a value. A pointer is a labeled box that holds anaddress— the location
ofanotherbox in memory.
intx=10;
int*p=&x;// p now holds the ADDRESS of x, not the value 10
printf("%d\n",x);// 10-> the value
printf("%p\n",&x);// 0x7ffee...-> the address of x
printf("%p\n",p);// 0x7ffee...-> same address, because p points to x
printf("%d\n",*p);// 10-> "dereference" p: go to that address, get the value
Two operators to internalize:
•&x— “address of x” (turns a value into a pointer)
•*p— “value at the address p points to” (turns a pointer back into a value)
Why DSA cares so much about pointers:every linked structure (linked lists, trees, graphs) is built from
nodes connected by pointers. Without pointers, you can’t build anything that isn’t a fixed-size array.
Pointers to pointersshow up constantly when a function needs to modify a pointer itself (not just what it
points to) — e.g., inserting a node at the head of a linked list needs to change what theheadvariable points
to, frominsidea function:
voidupdateHead(structNode**headRef){
// headRef is the address of the head pointer itself
*headRef=someNewNode;// this changes the actual head variable in the caller
}
This trips up almost everyone the first time. The rule of thumb:ifafunctionneedstopermanentlychange
what a pointer points to, it needs a pointer to that pointer.
0.2 Arrays and memory
An array is just a contiguous block of memory.arr[i]is really shorthand for*(arr + i)— “goisteps
past the start address and read the value there.” This is why array indices start at 0:arr[0]is*(arr + 0),
zero steps from the start.
intarr[5]={10,20,30,40,50};
printf("%d\n",arr[2]);// 30
printf("%d\n",*(arr+2));// 30 — identical
An array name, when used in most expressions, “decays” into a pointer to its first element. This is why you
can pass arrays to functions using a pointer parameter:
2

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
voidprintArray(int*arr,intsize){// same as int arr[]
for(inti=0;i<size;i++)
printf("%d",arr[i]);
}
Important gotcha:because arrays decay to pointers when passed to functions,sizeof(arr)insidea func-
tion that received the array as a parameter will NOT give you the array’s size — it gives you the size of a
pointer (usually 8 bytes). Always pass the size explicitly as a separate parameter.
0.3 Structs — building your own data types
A
struct
groups related variables under one name. This is how every custom data structure in this guide
gets built.
structPoint{
intx;
inty;
};
structPoint p1={3,4};
printf("%d,%d\n",p1.x,p1.y);// dot notation for direct access
structPoint*ptr=&p1;
printf("%d\n",ptr->x);// arrow notation when accessing through a pointer
// ptr->x is shorthand for (*ptr).x
To avoid writingstruct Pointeverywhere, most DSA code usestypedef:
typedefstructNode{
intdata;
structNode*next;
}Node;
Node n;// instead of struct Node n;
Throughout this guide, structs are written explicitly asstruct Nodefor clarity about what’s happening, but
you’ll seetypedef’d versions everywhere in the wild — they’re identical underneath.
0.4 Dynamic memory allocation
Arrays declared normally (int arr[10]) have a fixed size decided at compile time. Most real data structures
need to grow and shrink at runtime — that needs the heap.
FunctionWhat it does
malloc(size)Allocatessizebytes, contents are garbage
(uninitialized)
calloc(n, size)Allocatesnblocks ofsizebytes each, zeroed out
realloc(ptr, newSize)Resizes a previous allocation, preserving existing
contents
3

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
FunctionWhat it does
free(ptr)
Releases memory back to the system
structNode*newNode=(structNode*)malloc(sizeof(structNode));
if(newNode==NULL){
// malloc failed — always check this in real code
exit(1);
}
newNode->data=5;
newNode->next=NULL;
// ... use it ...
free(newNode);// give the memory back when you're done
The golden rule: everymallocneeds exactly one matchingfree.Forget to free and you get amem-
ory leak(memory that’s lost but never released). Free twice, or use memory after freeing it, and you get
undefined behavior— often a crash, sometimes silent corruption that shows up much later. In interviews,
casually mentioning that you’d free allocated nodes (even if you don’t write every free call) signals that you
understand ownership — interviewers notice this.
0.5 Recursion basics
A recursive function calls itself on a smaller version of the same problem, until it hits abase casesimple
enough to answer directly.
intfactorial(intn){
if(n<=1)return1;// base case — stops the recursion
returnn*factorial(n-1);// recursive case — smaller subproblem
}
Every recursive call gets pushed onto thecall stack. Callingfactorial(5)looks like this internally:
factorial(5)
-> 5 * factorial(4)
-> 4 * factorial(3)
-> 3 * factorial(2)
-> 2 * factorial(1)
-> returns 1  (base case hit)
<- returns 2 * 1 = 2
<- returns 3 * 2 = 6
<- returns 4 * 6 = 24
<- returns 5 * 24 = 120
Two things to always check when writing recursion: 1.Does every path eventually reach the base case?
If not, infinite recursion → stack overflow (a crash). 2.Is the problem actually getting smaller each call?
(n - 1, half the array, etc.)
4

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
Recursion will come back heavily in Part 6, but this mental model — “smaller subproblem + base case
+ trust that the recursive call works” — is the foundation for everything from tree traversals to dynamic
programming.
Interview Radar for Part 0:Interviewers rarely ask about pointers/structs directly, but they’ll absolutely
notice if you fumble&,*, or double pointers while coding a linked list problem live. This section is founda-
tion, not filler — most “silly mistakes” in DSA interviews are actually pointer mistakes.
