Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
Part 1: Complexity Analysis
1.1 Why this matters more than the code itself
In an interview, writingcorrectcode is the minimum bar. What separates a good answer from a great one is
whether you can say, unprompted:“this is O(n log n) time and O(n) space, and here’s why.”Interviewers
are evaluating whether you understand the cost of what you wrote, not just whether it compiles.
1.2 Big O notation, explained simply
Big O describes how theruntime or memoryof an algorithm grows as the input size (n) grows — not the
exact number of operations, just theshapeof the growth curve. It answers: “if I double the input, roughly
what happens to the work?”
NotationNameIf you doublen...Example
O(1)ConstantWork stays the sameAccessingarr[5]
O(log n)LogarithmicWork barely increases    Binary search
O(n)LinearWork doublesLooping through an
array once
O(n log n)LinearithmicWork slightly more than
doubles
Merge sort, quick sort
O(n²)QuadraticWork quadruplesNested loops over the
same array
O(2ⁿ)ExponentialWork squaresNaive recursive
Fibonacci
O(n!)FactorialExplodesBrute-force
permutations
Here’s that table as a growth picture — the gap between these classes gets brutal fast:
Operations
^
|O(n!)
|O(2^n)
|O(n^2)
|O(n log n)
|O(n)
|O(log n)
|  O(1)
+--------------------------------------------------> n (input size)
Atn = 20: O(log n) ≈ 4 operations. O(n) = 20. O(n²) = 400. O(2ⁿ) ≈ 1,000,000. That last jump is why “can
you avoid the exponential approach” is often the entire point of a DP question (more in Part 7).
1.3 How to actually read code for complexity
Rule 1 — sequential statements add:
6

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
for(inti=0;i<n;i++){...}// O(n)
for(inti=0;i<n;i++){...}// O(n)
// Total: O(n) + O(n) = O(2n) -> we drop constants -> O(n)
Big O drops constants and lower-order terms because we only care about growthshapefor largen. O(2n),
O(n + 5), and O(n) are all just written as O(n).
Rule 2 — nested loops multiply:
for(inti=0;i<n;i++){
for(intj=0;j<n;j++){...}// inner loop runs n times, for each of n outer
iterations↪
}
// Total: O(n * n) = O(n^2)
Rule 3 — a loop that halves the problem each time is O(log n):
while(n>1){
n=n/2;// how many times can you halve n before it hits 1? log2(n) times.
}
Rule 4 — recursive calls: count total calls, not just depth.A recursive function that makes 2 calls each
shrinkingnby 1 (like naive Fibonacci) branches into roughly 2ⁿ total calls — that’s where O(2ⁿ) comes from.
A recursive function that makes 1 call shrinkingnby half (like binary search) makes only O(log n) calls.
1.4 Best, Average, and Worst case
The same algorithm can have different complexities depending on the input. Quick sort, for instance:
•Best/Average case:O(n log n) — the pivot splits the array roughly evenly
•Worst case:O(n²) — the pivot is always the smallest or largest element (e.g., an already-sorted array
with a naive pivot choice)
When someone says “Big O,” they almost always meanworst caseunless stated otherwise — that’s the
guarantee you can rely on. Interviewers care about all three, but worst case is the default when you just say
“the complexity is...”.
1.5 Space complexity
Same idea, but for memory instead of time — how muchextramemory does the algorithm use beyond the
input itself, as a function ofn?
intsumArray(intarr[],intn){
intsum=0;// O(1) extra space — one variable, regardless of n
for(inti=0;i<n;i++)
sum+=arr[i];
returnsum;
}
int*doubleArray(intarr[],intn){
7

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
int*result=malloc(n*sizeof(int));// O(n) extra space — grows with input
for(inti=0;i<n;i++)
result[i]=arr[i]*2;
returnresult;
}
Don’t forget thecall stackcounts as space too — a recursive function with depthnuses O(n) space even if
it allocates no extra variables, because each pending call sits on the stack.
Interview Radar for Part 1:You will be asked “what’s the time complexity?” after nearly every single
problem you solve, without fail. Practice saying it out loud, unprompted, the moment you finish writing code
— don’t wait to be asked. If you can also state the space complexity and mention whether the time/space
could be traded off against each other, that’s a strong signal.
8

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
Part 2: Linear Data Structures
Linear data structures store elements in a sequence, one after another. This section covers the ones you’ll
use — and get asked to implement from memory — constantly.
2.1 Arrays
An array is the simplest data structure: a fixed-size, contiguous block of same-type elements, accessed by
index in O(1).
OperationComplexityWhy
Access by indexO(1)Direct address calculation:base
+ i * elementSize
Search (unsorted)O(n)Might have to check every
element
Search (sorted)O(log n)Binary search — see Part 5
Insert at endO(1)If space available
Insert at beginning/middleO(n)Everything after must shift right
DeleteO(n)Everything after must shift left
voidinsertAt(intarr[],int*n,intindex,intvalue){
for(inti=*n;i>index;i--)
arr[i]=arr[i-1];// shift everything right
arr[index]=value;
(*n)++;
}
voiddeleteAt(intarr[],int*n,intindex){
for(inti=index;i<*n-1;i++)
arr[i]=arr[i+1];// shift everything left
(*n)--;
}
2D arraysare stored row-major in C (row by row, contiguous):
intmatrix[3][4];// 3 rows, 4 columns
matrix[1][2]=7;// row 1, column 2
// Passing a 2D array to a function requires the column count at compile time:
voidprintMatrix(intmat[][4],introws){
for(inti=0;i<rows;i++)
for(intj=0;j<4;j++)
printf("%d",mat[i][j]);
}
Dynamic 2D arrays(when size isn’t known until runtime) are usually built as an array of pointers:
9

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
int**createMatrix(introws,intcols){
int**mat=(int**)malloc(rows*sizeof(int*));
for(inti=0;i<rows;i++)
mat[i]=(int*)malloc(cols*sizeof(int));
returnmat;
}
voidfreeMatrix(int**mat,introws){
for(inti=0;i<rows;i++)free(mat[i]);
free(mat);
}
2.2 Strings in C
C has no built-in string type — a string is just achararray terminated by a null byte'\0'. This null
terminator is the single most important thing to remember about C strings; forget it and every string function
reads into garbage memory.
charname[20]="Likith";
// In memory: 'L' 'i' 'k' 'i' 't' 'h' '\0' ??? ??? ...
//the '\0' marks where the actual string ends
Common library functions (#include <string.h>):
FunctionDoes
strlen(s)Length, not counting\0— O(n)
strcpy(dest, src)Copy src into dest
strcat(dest, src)Append src onto the end of dest
strcmp(a, b)0 if equal, <0 if a < b, >0 if a > b
strchr(s, c)Find first occurrence of char c
A classic interview exercise is implementing these yourself— it’s really testing whether you understand
the null terminator:
intmyStrlen(char*s){
intlen=0;
while(s[len]!='\0')len++;
returnlen;
}
voidreverseString(char*s){
intleft=0,right=myStrlen(s)-1;
while(left<right){
chartemp=s[left];
s[left]=s[right];
s[right]=temp;
left++;
right--;
