}
}
intisPalindrome(char*s){
intleft=0,right=myStrlen(s)-1;
while(left<right){
if(s[left]!=s[right])return0;
left++;
right--;
}
return1;
}
Interview Radar for Arrays & Strings:Reverse an array/string in place, find duplicates, rotate an array
by k, find the missing number in 1..n, check for anagram, longest common prefix, move all zeros to the end.
These are warm-up questions — expect them to be solved in under 5 minutes each with correct edge-case
handling (empty array, single element).
2.3 Linked Lists
A linked list stores elements asnodes, each holding data plus a pointer to the next node. Unlike arrays, nodes
are scattered in memory — connected by pointers, not by being next to each other.
[10 | *]--->[20 | *]--->[30 | *]--->[40 | NULL]
head
OperationArrayLinked List
Access by indexO(1)O(n) — must walk from head
Insert/delete at known positionO(n) — shiftingO(1) — if you have the pointer
Insert/delete at beginningO(n)O(1)
MemoryContiguous, fixed sizeScattered, grows dynamically
This tradeoff — slow access but fast insertion/deletion — is the whole reason linked lists exist, and it’s
exactly what interviewers probe when they ask “why would you use a linked list over an array here?”
Singly linked list — full implementation:
#include<stdio.h>
#include<stdlib.h>
structNode{
intdata;
structNode*next;
};
structNode*createNode(intdata){
structNode*newNode=(structNode*)malloc(sizeof(structNode));
newNode->data=data;
11

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
newNode->next=NULL;
returnnewNode;
}
// Note the double pointer: we need to modify the caller's head variable itself
voidinsertAtBeginning(structNode**head,intdata){
structNode*newNode=createNode(data);
newNode->next=*head;
*head=newNode;
}
voidinsertAtEnd(structNode**head,intdata){
structNode*newNode=createNode(data);
if(*head==NULL){
*head=newNode;
return;
}
structNode*temp=*head;
while(temp->next!=NULL)
temp=temp->next;
temp->next=newNode;
}
voiddeleteNode(structNode**head,intkey){
structNode*temp=*head;
structNode*prev=NULL;
if(temp!=NULL&&temp->data==key){// deleting the head itself
*head=temp->next;
free(temp);
return;
}
while(temp!=NULL&&temp->data!=key){
prev=temp;
temp=temp->next;
}
if(temp==NULL)return;// key not found
prev->next=temp->next;
free(temp);
}
voidprintList(structNode*head){
structNode*temp=head;
while(temp!=NULL){
printf("%d-> ",temp->data);
temp=temp->next;
}
printf("NULL\n");
12

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
}
intmain(){
structNode*head=NULL;
insertAtEnd(&head,10);
insertAtEnd(&head,20);
insertAtEnd(&head,30);
insertAtBeginning(&head,5);
printList(head);// 5 -> 10 -> 20 -> 30 -> NULL
deleteNode(&head,20);
printList(head);// 5 -> 10 -> 30 -> NULL
return0;
}
Reversing a linked list(the single most-asked linked list question — you should be able to write this cold):
structNode*reverseList(structNode*head){
structNode*prev=NULL;
structNode*curr=head;
while(curr!=NULL){
structNode*nextTemp=curr->next;// save next before overwriting
curr->next=prev;// reverse the pointer
prev=curr;// move prev forward
curr=nextTemp;// move curr forward
}
returnprev;// prev is the new head
}
Time: O(n), Space: O(1) — this iterative version beats a recursive one on space, which is worth saying out
loud in an interview.
Finding the middle node in one pass(fast/slow pointers — see Part 10):
structNode*findMiddle(structNode*head){
structNode*slow=head,*fast=head;
while(fast!=NULL&&fast->next!=NULL){
slow=slow->next;
fast=fast->next->next;// fast moves 2 steps for every 1 of slow
}
returnslow;// when fast hits the end, slow is at the middle
}
Detecting a cycle(Floyd’s algorithm — also fast/slow pointers):
inthasCycle(structNode*head){
structNode*slow=head,*fast=head;
while(fast!=NULL&&fast->next!=NULL){
slow=slow->next;
fast=fast->next->next;
if(slow==fast)return1;// they meet -> there's a cycle
}
13

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
return0;
}
The intuition: if fast is lapping slow on a loop, they must eventually land on the same node — like two
runners on a circular track where one is twice as fast.
Doubly linked list— each node also points backward, trading a bit of memory for O(1) backward traversal
and easier deletion (no need to trackprevseparately while walking):
structDNode{
intdata;
structDNode*next;
structDNode*prev;
};
structDNode*createDNode(intdata){
structDNode*newNode=(structDNode*)malloc(sizeof(structDNode));
newNode->data=data;
newNode->next=NULL;
newNode->prev=NULL;
returnnewNode;
}
voidinsertAtEndD(structDNode**head,intdata){
structDNode*newNode=createDNode(data);
if(*head==NULL){
*head=newNode;
return;
}
structDNode*temp=*head;
while(temp->next!=NULL)
temp=temp->next;
temp->next=newNode;
newNode->prev=temp;
}
voiddeleteDNode(structDNode**head,structDNode*delNode){
if(*head==delNode)*head=delNode->next;
if(delNode->next!=NULL)delNode->next->prev=delNode->prev;
if(delNode->prev!=NULL)delNode->prev->next=delNode->next;
free(delNode);
}
Circular linked list— the last node points back to the head instead of NULL. Used when you need to cycle
through elements repeatedly (e.g., round-robin CPU scheduling, a playlist on loop). The main implementa-
tion difference: your loop condition checkstemp->next != headinstead oftemp->next != NULL, and
you have to be careful not to loop forever.
InterviewRadarforLinkedLists:Reverse a list (iterative AND recursive), detect + find the start of a cycle,
merge two sorted lists, find the middle, remove the Nth node from the end, check if a list is a palindrome,
14

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
detect and remove duplicates. This is one of the highest-frequency topics in any DSA interview — get fluent
here.
2.4 Stacks — Last In, First Out (LIFO)
Think of a stack of plates: you can only add or remove from the top. The last plate you put on is the first
one you take off.
Operation   MeaningComplexity
pushAdd to topO(1)
popRemove from topO(1)
peek/topLook at top without removing  O(1)
isEmpty
Check if empty
O(1)
Array-based implementation:
#define MAX100
structStack{
intarr[MAX];
inttop;
};
voidinitStack(structStack*s){
s->top=-1;
}
intisEmpty(structStack*s){
returns->top==-1;
}
intisFull(structStack*s){
returns->top==MAX-1;
}
voidpush(structStack*s,intvalue){
if(isFull(s)){
printf("Stack Overflow\n");
return;
}
s->arr[++(s->top)]=value;
}
intpop(structStack*s){
if(isEmpty(s)){
printf("Stack Underflow\n");
return-1;
}
returns->arr[(s->top)--];
15

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
}
intpeek(structStack*s){
if(isEmpty(s))return-1;
returns->arr[s->top];
}
Alinked-list-basedstackavoidsthefixedMAXsize—pushbecomesinsertAtBeginningandpopbecomes
“remove and return the head.” Worth knowing both versions exist; the array version is what you’ll usually
code live because it’s faster to write correctly under pressure.
Classic application — checking balanced parentheses, a very common warm-up question:
intisBalanced(char*expr){
structStack s;
initStack(&s);
for(inti=0;expr[i]!='\0';i++){
charch=expr[i];
if(ch=='('||ch=='{'||ch=='['){
push(&s,ch);
}elseif(ch==')'||ch=='}'||ch==']'){
if(isEmpty(&s))return0;
inttop=pop(&s);
if((ch==')'&&top!='(')||
(ch=='}'&&top!='{')||
(ch==']'&&top!='['))
return0;
}
}
returnisEmpty(&s);// if anything's left unmatched, it's not balanced
}
Other classic stack uses: evaluating postfix expressions, converting infix to postfix, undo functionality, the
call stack itself (recursion IS a stack), and “next greater element” style problems.
2.5 Queues — First In, First Out (FIFO)
Think of a line at a shop counter: whoever joined first gets served first.
Operation  MeaningComplexity
enqueueAdd to the rearO(1)
dequeueRemove from the front  O(1)
frontPeek at the frontO(1)
A naive array queue(just incrementing front/rear) wastes space — once you dequeue a few elements, that
space at the front is never reused. The fix is acircularqueue, which wraps the index back to 0 using modulo:
16

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
#define MAX100
structQueue{
intarr[MAX];
intfront,rear,size;
};
voidinitQueue(structQueue*q){
q->front=0;
q->rear=-1;
q->size=0;
}
intisQueueEmpty(structQueue*q){
returnq->size==0;
}
intisQueueFull(structQueue*q){
returnq->size==MAX;
}
voidenqueue(structQueue*q,intvalue){
if(isQueueFull(q)){
printf("Queue Overflow\n");
return;
}
q->rear=(q->rear+1)%MAX;// wrap around
q->arr[q->rear]=value;
q->size++;
}
intdequeue(structQueue*q){
if(isQueueEmpty(q)){
printf("Queue Underflow\n");
return-1;
}
intvalue=q->arr[q->front];
q->front=(q->front+1)%MAX;// wrap around
q->size--;
returnvalue;
}
Other queue variants worth knowing by name:
•Deque (double-ended queue):insertion/deletion allowed at both front and rear. Useful for sliding
window problems (Part 10).
•Priority Queue:each element has a priority; dequeue always removes the highest (or lowest) priority
element, not just the oldest. Almost always implemented with aheapunderneath (Part 3.4) — this is
why heaps and priority queues are taught together.
