Terminology you need to be fluent in:
•Root:the top node, no parent
•Leaf:a node with no children
•Height of a node:longest path from that node down to a leaf
•Depth of a node:path length from the root down to that node
•Height of the tree:height of the root
3.2 Binary Trees
Abinary treerestricts each node to at most 2 children — conventionally calledleftandright.
structTreeNode{
intdata;
structTreeNode*left;
structTreeNode*right;
};
structTreeNode*createTreeNode(intdata){
structTreeNode*node=(structTreeNode*)malloc(sizeof(structTreeNode));
node->data=data;
node->left=node->right=NULL;
returnnode;
}
Traversals— the order you visit nodes in. There are 4 standard ones, and knowing all of them (plus being
able to code them without hesitation) is non-negotiable for interviews.
// Depth-first traversals (recursive) — all O(n) time, O(h) space where h = height
voidpreorder(structTreeNode*root){// Root -> Left -> Right
