3.5 Heaps
A heap is a binary tree with one extra rule, stored efficiently as a plain array (no pointers needed):
•Min-heap:every parent is ≤ its children (so the smallest element is always the root)
•Max-heap:every parent is ≥ its children (so the largest element is always the root)
Because a heap is always acompletebinary tree (filled left to right, no gaps), it can live in an array with
simple index math instead of needing pointers:
For a node at index i (0-indexed):
parent(i) = (i - 1) / 2
left(i)   = 2*i + 1
right(i)  = 2*i + 2
voidswap(int*a,int*b){
inttemp=*a;
*a=*b;
*b=temp;
}
// "Sift down" — fixes a single violation by pushing the wrong element down
voidminHeapify(intarr[],intn,inti){
intsmallest=i;
intleft=2*i+1;
intright=2*i+2;
if(left<n&&arr[left]<arr[smallest])
smallest=left;
if(right<n&&arr[right]<arr[smallest])
smallest=right;
if(smallest!=i){
swap(&arr[i],&arr[smallest]);
minHeapify(arr,n,smallest);// the swap might have broken things further down
}
}
// Build a heap from an unsorted array — starts from the last non-leaf node
voidbuildMinHeap(intarr[],intn){
for(inti=n/2-1;i>=0;i--)
minHeapify(arr,n,i);
}
voidinsertHeap(intarr[],int*n,intvalue){
(*n)++;
inti=*n-1;
arr[i]=value;
// "Sift up" — bubble the new value up until the heap property holds
while(i!=0&&arr[(i-1)/2]>arr[i]){
