Heaps are the standard way to implement a Priority Queue— whenever you need “give me the small-
est/largest remaining item, repeatedly, efficiently,” reach for a heap. This shows up constantly: Dijkstra’s
algorithm, “top K elements” problems, merging K sorted lists, median-finding.
Heap Sort— using the heap property to sort an array in place:
voidmaxHeapify(intarr[],intn,inti){
intlargest=i;
intleft=2*i+1;
intright=2*i+2;
if(left<n&&arr[left]>arr[largest])largest=left;
if(right<n&&arr[right]>arr[largest])largest=right;
if(largest!=i){
swap(&arr[i],&arr[largest]);
maxHeapify(arr,n,largest);
}
}
voidheapSort(intarr[],intn){
for(inti=n/2-1;i>=0;i--)// build max heap
maxHeapify(arr,n,i);
for(inti=n-1;i>0;i--){
swap(&arr[0],&arr[i]);// move current max to the end
maxHeapify(arr,i,0);// re-heapify the reduced heap
}
}
