Time: O(n log n) always (no worst-case surprises like quicksort). Space: O(1) — sorts in place. More on
where this fits among other sorts in Part 4.
3.6 Hashing
Everything so far has a search cost of at least O(log n). Hashing gets you O(1) average-case search, insert,
and delete — the tradeoff is you give up ordering entirely.
The idea: ahashfunctionconverts a key into an array index, so you can jump straight to where a value lives
instead of searching for it.
inthashFunction(intkey,inttableSize){
returnkey%tableSize;// simple example — real hash functions are more elaborate
}
The collision problem:two different keys can hash to the same index (e.g., both13 % 10and23 % 10
equal3). Two standard fixes:
Chaining— each array slot holds a linked list of all keys that hashed there:
#define TABLE_SIZE10
structHashNode{
intkey;
intvalue;
structHashNode*next;
};
structHashNode*hashTable[TABLE_SIZE]={NULL};// all slots start empty
inthashFunc(intkey){
returnkey%TABLE_SIZE;
}
voidinsertHash(intkey,intvalue){
intindex=hashFunc(key);
structHashNode*newNode=(structHashNode*)malloc(sizeof(structHashNode));
newNode->key=key;
newNode->value=value;
newNode->next=hashTable[index];// insert at head of the chain
hashTable[index]=newNode;
}
intsearchHash(intkey){
intindex=hashFunc(key);
structHashNode*curr=hashTable[index];
while(curr!=NULL){
if(curr->key==key)returncurr->value;
curr=curr->next;
}
return-1;// not found
}
27

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
Open addressing (linear probing)— no linked lists; if a slot is taken, keep checking the next slot until you
find an empty one:
inttable[TABLE_SIZE];
intoccupied[TABLE_SIZE]={0};
voidinsertProbing(intkey){
intindex=key%TABLE_SIZE;
while(occupied[index]){// slot taken? try the next one
index=(index+1)%TABLE_SIZE;
}
table[index]=key;
occupied[index]=1;
}
Load factor= (number of elements) / (table size). Once this gets too high (typically > 0.7), performance
degrades toward O(n) because chains get long / probing takes many steps — this is why real hash tables
automatically resize (rehash into a bigger table) as they fill up.
Operation  Average case  Worst case (many collisions)
InsertO(1)O(n)
SearchO(1)O(n)
DeleteO(1)O(n)
Hash tables are what powerHashMap/dict/unordered_mapin other languages. In C interviews, you’re
more likely to be asked to design a simple hash table (as above) than to use one, since C doesn’t ship with a
built-in hash map.
