tioning if asked “which would you pick.”
4.2 The O(n log n) sorts — what you’d actually use
Merge Sort— divide and conquer: split the array in half, sort each half recursively, then merge the two
sorted halves back together.
voidmerge(intarr[],intleft,intmid,intright){
intn1=mid-left+1;
intn2=right-mid;
int*L=(int*)malloc(n1*sizeof(int));
int*R=(int*)malloc(n2*sizeof(int));
for(inti=0;i<n1;i++)L[i]=arr[left+i];
for(intj=0;j<n2;j++)R[j]=arr[mid+1+j];
inti=0,j=0,k=left;
while(i<n1&&j<n2)
arr[k++]=(L[i]<=R[j])?L[i++]:R[j++];
while(i<n1)arr[k++]=L[i++];
while(j<n2)arr[k++]=R[j++];
free(L);
free(R);
}
voidmergeSort(intarr[],intleft,intright){
if(left<right){
intmid=left+(right-left)/2;
mergeSort(arr,left,mid);
mergeSort(arr,mid+1,right);
merge(arr,left,mid,right);
}
}
Time: O(n log n)guaranteed— best, average, and worst case are all the same, which is a real advantage.
Space: O(n) for the temporary arrays.Stable(equal elements keep their relative order) — matters if you’re
sorting objects by one field but want ties broken by original order.
Quick Sort— pick a pivot, partition the array so smaller elements are left of it and larger are right, then
recursively sort each side.
intpartition(intarr[],intlow,inthigh){
intpivot=arr[high];// choosing the last element as pivot (simple, common choice)
inti=low-1;
for(intj=low;j<high;j++){
if(arr[j]<pivot){
i++;
swap(&arr[i],&arr[j]);
