Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
}
}
swap(&arr[i+1],&arr[high]);
returni+1;// final position of the pivot
}
voidquickSort(intarr[],intlow,inthigh){
if(low<high){
intpi=partition(arr,low,high);
quickSort(arr,low,pi-1);
quickSort(arr,pi+1,high);
}
}
Time: O(n log n) average, butO(n²) worst case— happens when the pivot choice is consistently bad (e.g.,
always picking the last element on an already-sorted array). Space: O(log n) for the recursion stack (in-place,
no extra arrays needed, unlike merge sort). In practice, quick sort is usuallyfasterthan merge sort despite
the worse worst-case, because of better cache locality and lower constant factors — a good thing to mention
if asked to compare them.
Heap Sort— covered fully in section 3.5. Time: O(n log n) guaranteed, Space: O(1) — better worst-case
space than both merge sort and quick sort, but generally slower in practice due to poor cache locality (jumping
around the array via index math rather than accessing sequentially).
4.3 Linear-time sorts (special cases)
Counting Sort— when you know values fall in a small range (e.g., 0-100), you can sort in O(n + k) by
counting occurrences of each value:
voidcountingSort(intarr[],intn,intmaxVal){
int*count=(int*)calloc(maxVal+1,sizeof(int));
int*output=(int*)malloc(n*sizeof(int));
for(inti=0;i<n;i++)count[arr[i]]++;
for(inti=1;i<=maxVal;i++)count[i]+=count[i-1];// prefix sum = final
positions↪
for(inti=n-1;i>=0;i--){
output[count[arr[i]]-1]=arr[i];
count[arr[i]]--;
}
for(inti=0;i<n;i++)arr[i]=output[i];
