Part 6: Recursion, Backtracking & Divide-and-Conquer
6.1 Recursion deep dive
Part 0 covered the mechanics. Here’s the mental model that makes recursive problems tractable:trust the
recursive call to correctly solve the smaller subproblem, and focus only on how to combine that result
into the answer for your current call.Don’t try to trace the entire call tree in your head for every problem
— that’s what got you the base case + recursive case reasoning in the first place.
Why naive recursive Fibonacci is a trap:
intfib(intn){
if(n<=1)returnn;
returnfib(n-1)+fib(n-2);
}
This looks innocent but is O(2ⁿ) — exponential — because it recomputes the same subproblems over and
over:
fib(5)
/\
fib(4)fib(3)
/\/\
fib(3)    fib(2)fib(2)   fib(1)
/    \/  \/  \
fib(2) fib(1) fib(1)fib(0) fib(1)fib(0)
/  \
fib(1)fib(0)
Noticefib(3)gets computed twice,fib(2)three times. This wasted, repeated work is exactly the problem
Dynamic Programming solves (Part 7) — by remembering results instead of recomputing them, the same
problem drops from O(2ⁿ) to O(n).
6.2 Backtracking
Backtracking is recursion with a twist: try a choice, recurse, and if it doesn’t work out,undo the choice
(“backtrack”) and try the next option. It’s how you systematically explore all possibilities without brute-
forcing every combination blindly — you prune branches the moment you know they can’t work.
The general template:
voidbacktrack(/* state */){
if(/* base case: found a solution */){
// record or print it
return;
}
for(/* each choice available */){
// make the choice
if(/* choice is valid */){
backtrack(/* updated state */);
}
