6.3 Divide and Conquer
A problem-solving paradigm with three steps:Dividethe problem into smaller subproblems,Conquereach
subproblem recursively,Combinethe results into the final answer. You’ve already seen this pattern twice:
•Merge Sort:Divide the array in half → Conquer (sort each half recursively) → Combine (merge the
sorted halves)
•Binary Search:Divide the search space in half → Conquer (search the correct half) → Combine
(trivial — just return the result, no half was discarded for nothing)
•QuickSort:Divide via partitioning → Conquer (sort each side) → Combine (trivial — no merge step
needed, since partitioning already places elements correctly relative to each other)
How to estimate the complexity of a divide-and-conquer algorithm(the simplified Master Theorem in-
tuition): if a problem of sizensplits intoasubproblems each of sizen/b, plusO(n^d)work to combine
them, the total complexity depends on comparinga(how much you branch) againstb^d(how much each
level shrinks):
•If splitting dominates (a > b^d): complexity is roughly O(n^(log_b a))
•If combining dominates (a < b^d): complexity is roughly O(n^d)
•If balanced (a = b^d): complexity is O(n^d log n) — this is exactly merge sort’s case: 2 subproblems
of size n/2, O(n) to merge → O(n log n)
