7.2 Dynamic Programming — the big idea
DP applies when a problem has two properties: 1.Overlappingsubproblems— the same smaller problems
get solved repeatedly (likefib(3)above) 2.Optimal substructure— the optimal solution to the whole
problem can be built from optimal solutions to its subproblems
The fix for overlapping subproblems is simple:remember answers you’ve already computed.There are
two ways to do this:
Memoization (top-down):write the recursive solution normally, but cache results in an array/table before
returning them.
intmemo[50];
intfibMemo(intn){
if(n<=1)returnn;
if(memo[n]!=-1)returnmemo[n];// already solved — reuse it
memo[n]=fibMemo(n-1)+fibMemo(n-2);
returnmemo[n];
}
// Before calling: initialize memo[] to all -1 (meaning "not yet computed")
This alone takes Fibonacci from O(2ⁿ) to O(n) — same recursive structure, but each subproblem is now
solved exactly once.
Tabulation (bottom-up):build the table iteratively from the smallest subproblems up, no recursion at all.
intfibTabulation(intn){
if(n<=1)returnn;
intdp[n+1];
