Part 10: Interview Problem-Solving Patterns
This section is different from the rest — instead of a specific data structure, these arereusabletemplatesthat
solve a huge fraction of interview array/string/linked-list problems once you recognize the pattern. Spotting
which pattern applies is often the actual skill being tested.
10.1 Two Pointers
Use two indices moving through a structure (often from both ends, or one ahead of the other) instead of
nested loops — turns many O(n²) brute-force approaches into O(n).
Pair with a given sum in a sorted array:
voidpairSum(intarr[],intn,inttarget){
intleft=0,right=n-1;
while(left<right){
intsum=arr[left]+arr[right];
if(sum==target){
printf("Pair found:%d+%d\n",arr[left],arr[right]);
return;
}elseif(sum<target){
left++;// need a bigger sum -> move left pointer up
}else{
right--;// need a smaller sum -> move right pointer down
}
}
printf("No pair found\n");
}
Removeduplicatesfromasortedarrayinplace— a slow pointer tracks the “write” position, a fast pointer
scans ahead:
intremoveDuplicates(intarr[],intn){
if(n==0)return0;
intslow=0;
for(intfast=1;fast<n;fast++){
if(arr[fast]!=arr[slow]){
slow++;
arr[slow]=arr[fast];
}
}
returnslow+1;// new length
}
10.2 Sliding Window
For problems about contiguous subarrays/substrings, avoid recomputing the whole window from scratch
each time — instead, slide it: remove the element leaving the window, add the element entering it.
Maximum sum subarray of fixed size k:
54

Data Structures & Algorithms in C — Interview Guide
intmaxSumSubarray(intarr[],intn,intk){
intwindowSum=0;
for(inti=0;i<k;i++)windowSum+=arr[i];// first window
intmaxSum=windowSum;
for(inti=k;i<n;i++){
windowSum+=arr[i]-arr[i-k];// slide: add new element, drop the oldest
if(windowSum>maxSum)maxSum=windowSum;
}
returnmaxSum;
}
This is O(n) instead of the O(n×k) you’d get recomputing every window’s sum from scratch.
Variable-size window(e.g., longest substring without repeating characters) works the same way, but the
window grows/shrinks based on a condition rather than a fixed sizek— grow the right edge until the condi-
tion breaks, then shrink the left edge until it’s valid again.
10.3 Fast & Slow Pointers
Already seen in Part 2.3 (cycle detection, finding the middle of a linked list) — worth calling out as its own
named pattern because once you recognize “cycle” or “middle element in one pass,” this is almost always
the tool.
10.4 Top-K Elements (via Heap)
Whenever a problem asks for the K largest/smallest/most-frequent elements, a heap (Part 3.5) is almost
always the efficient answer — maintain a heap of size K as you scan through the data, giving O(n log k)
instead of the O(n log n) a full sort would cost.
// Conceptual approach for "K largest elements":
// 1. Build a MIN-heap of the first K elements.
// 2. For each remaining element: if it's bigger than the heap's minimum (the root),
//    remove the root and insert the new element.
// 3. Whatever remains in the heap at the end is your K largest elements.
// Using a MIN-heap for "K largest" feels backwards at first — the trick is that the
// smallest element in your current top-K is exactly the one you're willing to evict.
10.5 A general framework for approaching a new problem live
When you’re handed a problem you haven’t seen before, working through these steps out loud is often worth
more than jumping straight to code:
1.Clarify— restate the problem in your own words, ask about edge cases (empty input? duplicates?
negative numbers?) and constraints (how large cannget? — this often hints at the expected complex-
ity).
2.Work a small example by hand— this frequently reveals the pattern before you’ve written a line of
code.
