3.State the brute-force approach first, even if it’s slow — it shows you can solve it at all, and gives
you a complexity baseline to improve on.
4.Look for a pattern from Part 10, or a data structure from Parts 2-3 that fits the access pattern you
need (need fast lookup? hashing. Need sorted order maintained? BST/heap. Need “last thing I saw”?
stack. Need “first thing I saw”? queue.).
5.Code it, narrating as you go.
6.Test itagainst your hand-worked example, and at least one edge case.
7.State the final time and space complexity, unprompted.
