11.2 Common mistakes that cost people otherwise-good interviews
•Jumping straight to codewithout clarifying the problem or stating a plan first — interviewers are
often evaluating your process, not just your final answer.
•Going silent while coding.Narrate your thinking, even the mundane parts (“I’ll use a hash map here
to get O(1) lookups instead of scanning the array again”).
•Not testing your own code.Walk through your solution on the example by hand before declaring
you’re done.
•Forgetting to state complexityunprompted — don’t wait to be asked.
•Ignoring edge cases— empty input, single element, all duplicates, negative numbers. Mention them
even if the interviewer doesn’t ask.
