11.4 Practicing beyond this guide
This document gives you the concepts and clean reference implementations. Building actual speed and pat-
tern recognition comes from solving problems yourself — sites like LeetCode, GeeksforGeeks, and Hack-
erRank are standard for this, and most companies’ interview questions are drawn from a fairly well-known
pool of problem types once you’ve seen enough of them. A reasonable rhythm: pick one topic from Tier
1 above, solve 3-5 problems on it back to back so the pattern actually sinks in, then move to the next topic
rather than jumping randomly between categories.
When you get stuck on a problem, give yourself a real 15-20 minutes before looking at a hint — the struggle
is where the pattern recognition actually gets built. But don’t spend an hour stuck either; look at the approach,
understandwhyit works, close it, and re-solve it yourself from scratch a day or two later. That re-solving
step is what actually moves a pattern from “I’ve seen this” to “I can produce this under pressure,” which is
the only version of the skill that helps you in an actual interview.
End of guide. Good luck — you’ve got this.
